<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="230" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,325,638]" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,273,325,350]" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[353,500,325,350]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1921,1943]" captionTargetBox="[150,1424,691,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[150,1436,690,1900]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Ptilothyris loxocasis Meyrick (18A–E) and Ptilothyris nausicaa Meyrick (18F). A, Lectotype, male, in RMCA; B, Labels of lectotype; C, Male genitalia, gen. slide no. CIS-7221, with a close-up of uncus and of juxta; D, Phallus, with a close-up of cornutus; E, Abdomen; F, P. nausicaa, holotype, male, in NHMUK." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594895/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">Figs. 18A, B</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Meyrick" authorityYear="1938" box="[521,750,325,350]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="230" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="loxocasis">
<emphasis box="[521,750,325,350]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">Ptilothyris loxocasis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has superficially a little different characters from its allies of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Walsingham" authorityYear="1897" box="[274,392,361,386]" class="Insecta" family="Lecithoceridae" genus="Ptilothyris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="29" pageNumber="230" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[274,392,361,386]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">Ptilothyris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, by having the forewing more or less short with an oblique, broad, orange-white fascia medially, and the antenna not distinctly pectinate. However, the male genitalia dissected from the 
<typeStatus box="[1309,1357,398,422]" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">type</typeStatus>
in the RMCA matches well to those of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="29" pageNumber="230" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="29.[151,1436,325,638]" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">
<emphasis box="[199,366,469,494]" italics="true" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[384,538,469,494]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1921,1943]" captionTargetBox="[150,1424,691,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[150,1436,690,1900]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 18. Ptilothyris loxocasis Meyrick (18A–E) and Ptilothyris nausicaa Meyrick (18F). A, Lectotype, male, in RMCA; B, Labels of lectotype; C, Male genitalia, gen. slide no. CIS-7221, with a close-up of uncus and of juxta; D, Phallus, with a close-up of cornutus; E, Abdomen; F, P. nausicaa, holotype, male, in NHMUK." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2594895/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="230">Figs. 18C, D</figureCitation>
). Uncus broadened caudally with a median protrusion. Basal plate of gnathos with broadly developed median lobe and small lateral lobes; median process large, strongly curved beyond 2/3. Juxta large, with slender, digitate process on anterior margin, lacking caudal lobes. Phallus slender, shorter than valve, apically extending dorsal margin heavily sclerotized, with round apex; cornuti consisting of two short lows of spines in apical area.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
